Brooks Hawthorne

Brooks Hawthorne

  • son of Margaret (Mitchell) and Nathaniel Hawthorne
    • fourth oldest of his family, younger twin of Elwyn Hawthorne
  • boy, trans
    • he/him
  • gay asexual
  • starts the series at 12 and ends at 19
  • born July 11th, 2002
  • Namesake: E. B. White
  • Ability: Trumpet of the Swan
    • Ability Details: This ability manifests as a trumpet which must be played to activate the ability, and acts almost like a "call to action", soothing the fears and worries of a subject which surround an action they want to take, and compelling them to do it. While this ability does not necessarily force a subject to do something, its effects have been described as "hypnotic" and nearly impossible to break out of the longer the instrument is played. It can affect a large number of people at one time — anyone within earshot — and as such, it is a very powerful ability.
  • Affiliation: mainly just the Guild Undead at first, and even then he's really only there because of Elwyn, not because he particularly has any interest in Zelda Jr.'s schemes (though he does think of her as a friend); later on, he also aligns himself with the Apprentices of the ADA, as well as the ADA itself, and the Gunslinger Kids.
  • Level at which I think about them: medium
  • Brief Notes
    • Brooks is a typically quiet young man, and can usually be found in an isolated, quiet place with his nose in a book, or practicing his trumpet (not the one summoned by his ability, but a regular one). Unlike his older twin sister, Elwyn, Brooks is not someone who would be considered easy-going, friendly, or approachable; in fact, he is quite the opposite of these things, and almost always has a scowl on his face. His family frequently irritates him, as he states that they are "crazy, noisy, and never leave [him] alone", though he also makes sure to state that he loves them, and they are important to him despite his distaste for just about all of their family ventures. It is a wonder, then, how he managed to befriend Zelda Jr., or why he eventually chooses to date Mikhail Gogol, both of whom are nothing like him in terms of enjoying peace and quiet (they are actually rather chaotic).
    • Brooks is a smart boy, though he can be out of touch with people his age, preferring to be in the company of people who are older, or people more like his father, Nathaniel. He gets along best with his oldest sister, Susan, who is more like him than most of the others. He also almost always carries an inordinate amount of weapons on his person, and has a reputation of being quite the fighter. That said, Brooks trends towards deliberate inaction; he will not do something as taxing as fighting, or even something as simple as folding his clothes, without being told or urged to do so first. When asked why, he responds that he is "saving his energy", though he never elaborates on what he is saving his energy for.
